content:
Caution-Almost x-rated Pic: My future stepson, Zach Berman, scribes quite a tribute to The Captain, and he's just 17 years old with dreams of becoming a sports broadcaster:

Every sports fan has their idol growing up. Some kids grew up watching Joe Montana, or Michael Jordan. Maybe your guy was Wayne Gretzky, or Tom Brady. Or you could have your wall adorned with LeBron James memorabilia, or have memorized every single one of Peyton Manning's milestones. You stared at your TV in awe as Sidney Crosby sped down the ice towards the net. Or maybe, your "saving" grace was a signed jersey of Martin Brodeur. My idol growing up was Derek Jeter. When I was 4 years old, my grandpa installed a life size cardboard cutout of Derek Jeter on my bedroom wall, and he still has a picture of me staring up at that cut-out in awe. I was never a baseball player and I never made it past Tee-ball in kindergarten, yet Derek Jeter was my idol in more ways than just how many times he could hit a baseball. I watched him come up in the clutch time after time, he never gave up. When he would dive into the stands, or make that signature "jump throw" of his, I would feel personally inspired. One day, I was at camp, and overheard that he had hit his 3,000th hit, by way of a home run. I didn't even get to watch the highlight for another six weeks, and yet, that contributed to having one of the best summers of my life. Years passed, and DJ got old. I remember watching him play his last game in The Bronx, and when he hit that walk-off single, I remember feeling so bittersweet, that awesome feeling of "yay, we won!" and the dejection of "that's the last time I'll ever see that live.". Now, my idol has a plaque in Monument Park, and it's almost as if a dream has come true. I have watched my favorite player become a Yankee legend right before my eyes. I hope to be there in person when he gets inducted in Cooperstown. Thank you, Derek Jeter, for so many memories that I as a baseball fan, and a Yankees fan, will cherish forever...
name: Brian Thompson NBC NY
